text: Convergent Synthesis of Tetrasaccharide Fragment of Cervimycin K Jihun Kang and Young Ho Rhee* ABSTRACT: A new synthetic approach toward oligosaccharides consisting only of 2,3,6-trideoxypyranoglycosides is reported. The key feature is highlighted by the convergent approach that allows the introduction of the aglycon moiety in the late stage of the synthesis. As an illustrative example, the tetrasaccharide portion of cervimycin K was prepared as cyclohexyl glycoside. 2-Deoxyoligosaccharides are present in numerous bioactive natural products as a conjugate form to complex aglycon moieties. The length and structure of these oligosaccharides are reported to have a signiﬁcant eﬀect on the bioactivities of the natural products.1 Thus, the stereocontrolled synthesis of 2-deoxyoligosaccharides represents one of the most funda- topics in glycochemistry.2,3 This topic has been mental considered very challenging because of the lack of stereo- directing appendages at the 2 position. This problem is particularly well-addressed by oligosaccharides consisting only of 2,3,6-trideoxypyranoglycosides (such as amicetose or rhodinose) linked by both α- or β- anomeric conﬁgurations. They constitute the glycosidic part of several natural products such as lycoperdinoside B,4 amicenomycin A,5 and cervimycin K6 (Scheme 1). Despite the relatively short length and simple structure of their stereocontrolled syntheses have been very limited in conventional glycochem- istry, because of the anomeric conﬁguration.7

Recently, O’Doherty reported a potential solution to this problem based upon the iterative use of the Pd-catalyzed reaction of a pyranose unit (A in Scheme 1).8−11 Later, Tang further elaborated on the stereodivergent coupling by introducing related catalytic asymmetric transformations.9 This de novo approach represents a signiﬁcant advance in the synthesis of 2,3,6-trideoxyoligosaccharides. However, incorpo- ration of the method into the total synthesis needs to overcome another hurdle in that structurally complex aglycons should be introduced in an early stage and carried through the subsequent stepwise oligosaccharide synthesis. In this regard, a convergent method that couples the aglycon and glycon portions in a late stage would be highly advantageous. Upon the basis of these precedents, we envisioned that an analogous approach can successfully fulﬁll the above-mentioned goal in the synthesis of 2,3,6-trideox- yoligosaccharides. As a proof-of-concept example, we report here a convergent synthesis of the tetrasaccharide moiety of antibacterial cervimycin K as a cyclohexyl glycoside.14,15 From a retrosynthetic viewpoint, the synthesis of target 1 necessitates preparation of ene-alkoxyallene 2 (Scheme 2). reaction in the presence of Pd2(dba)3 (2.5 mol %), standard (S,S)-Trost ligand L (5 mol %), and triethylamine (0.1 equiv) in toluene at 40 °C for 2 h generated the acyclic acetal 10 in 94% yield. Even though the diastereoselectivity of this reaction could not be veriﬁed at this stage, we decided to see if the RCM reaction of this compound would deliver the desired trisaccharide 11 (path A, Scheme 4). A preliminary reaction using a ﬁrst generation Grubbs catalyst was very slow. Switching to a second generation catalyst (10 mol %) signiﬁcantly improved the conversion (>90%). However, the target compound 11 was obtained in only 20% yield. Interestingly, two additional compounds 12 and 13 containing a dihydrofuran skeleton were also obtained in signiﬁcant 76% combined yield. Apparently, these compounds are formed by the ring-rearrangement metathesis (RRM) of 10 (path B, Scheme 4).17 Subjection of 11 to similar conditions again produced 12 and 13 as the major products. This result strongly suggests that the products are formed in a reversible manner. To assess the diastereoselectivity of the Pd-catalyzed reaction, we attempted the synthesis of 14 (diastereomeric to 10) using an enantiomeric (R,R)-ligand. As depicted in Scheme 4, this to be signiﬁcantly slower. Complete reaction turned out assumption of the starting materials required the use of 10 mol % Pd2(dba)3 precatalyst. In this case, 14 was obtained in 86% yield. Because the 1H NMR spectrum of this compound was indistinguishable from 10, we performed the RCM reaction of 14. Again, this reaction produced a mixture of desired 15 and dihydrofuran derivatives analogous to 12 and 13. Even though https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.orglett.1c01404 Org. Lett. 2021, 23, 4468−4472

chromatographic separation of 15 was troublesome, it could be puriﬁed by recrystallization from the crude mixture. The 1H NMR spectra of 11 and 15 with respect to the newly generated stereocenter were clearly distinguishable, thus conﬁrming the excellent ligand-driven stereoselectivity in the Pd-catalyzed reactions (for the detailed analysis, see the Supporting Information). Because the synthesis of trisaccharide moiety 11 by way of RCM reaction was unsuccessful, we decided to carry the acyclic acetal 10 forward without RCM reaction. For this purpose, compound 10 was ﬁrst converted into allene 16 using the procedure optimized in Scheme 3 (for detailed information, see the Supporting Information). Then, we examined the sequential Pd−Ru catalysis of this compound using primary alcohol 17 or secondary alcohol 18 as the coupling partner. A preliminary reaction of 16 with 17 in the presence of an (R,R)-ligand under optimized conditions smoothly proceeded to produce the adduct in 93% yield with 21:1 ratio. The subsequent RCM reaction was sluggish. Complete conversion required the use of 30 mol % of a second generation Grubbs catalyst. Nevertheless, the desired tetra- saccharide 19a was obtained in 92% yield apparently with no competition from the RRM reaction (Table 1).18 Using an Table 1. In the case of secondary alcohol 18, the Pd-catalyzed coupling reaction turned out to be slower, presumably due to the increased steric congestion of the substrate. Using a higher loading of Pd2(dba)3 (10 mol %) was necessary to obtain the acyclic adduct in high 90% yield. The subsequent RCM reaction smoothly proceeded to give 20a in 86% yield. As depicted in Scheme 5, this method aﬀorded 21 in 91% yield.19 Removal of the Scheme 5. Synthesis of Target Compound 1

benzyl group proceeded smoothly by using a Pd/C catalyst under a hydrogen atmosphere, which delivered target compound 1 in 98% yield. The structure of 1 depicted in Scheme 5 was rigorously veriﬁed by various two-dimensional NMR spectroscopic techniques. (for detailed information, see the Supporting Information). Overall, tetrasaccharide 1 was assembled by the asymmetric sequential metal catalysis (Pd− Ru−Pd) from commercially available starting material 5. On the basis of a ligand-driven stereodivergent process, various stereoisomers of 1 can also be accessed with comparable eﬃciency to that for the naturally occurring structure. In summary, we developed a new synthetic strategy toward 2,3,6-trideoxyoligosaccharide. Remarkably, the convergent nature makes the method particularly amenable to the total synthesis of the related natural products. As an illustrative tetrasaccharide moiety in example, cervimycin K has been achieved. Currently, we are working on expanding of the scope of our de novo strategy to other oligosaccharides as well as on the total synthesis of related natural products.
